{"name":"Java Security Structure","id":20,"content":"<p>Java has some inbuilt security mechanism and allows you to extend security through many APIs.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h2><span style=\"color:#2c3e50;\"><span style=\"font-family:Lucida Sans Unicode,Lucida Grande,sans-serif;\">How secure is Java?</span></span></h2>\n\n<p>Security provided by JRE itself:</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Access Control to JVM Resources</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Rule-Based classloading and bytecode verification (that the bytecode is consistent with specifications of a trustworthy compiler)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Allows&nbsp;signing code and assigning levels of capability</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Policy-driven access to Java applets downloaded by a Web browser</p>\n\n<p>JDK provides a command line utility &#39;keytool&#39; for&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Creating JKS and JCEKS keystores</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Generate and store keys and their associated&nbsp;X.509v1 certificates</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;generate Certificate Signing Requests (CSR)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;import and store trusted certificates</p>\n\n<h2><span style=\"color:#2c3e50;\"><span style=\"font-family:Lucida Sans Unicode,Lucida Grande,sans-serif;\">What is Java Keystore?</span></span></h2>\n\n<p>The Java keystore is a protected database that stores keys and trusted certificate entries for those keys.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;It contains a private key and a chain of certificates that allows authentication with corresponding public keys.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Each entry in the keystore is identified by a unique alias.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>The Java keystore follows a cryptographic standard known as PKCS#12, which provides a way to securely store multiple keys and certificates in a password-protected file</p>\n\n<p>With the release of J2SE 5.0, the Java environment introduced the support for Cryptographic Token Interface Standard (referred to as PKCS#11) which defines native programming interfaces to cryptographic tokens, such as hardware cryptographic accelerators and smart cards.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h2><span style=\"color:#2c3e50;\"><span style=\"font-family:Lucida Sans Unicode,Lucida Grande,sans-serif;\">How can we extend and implement custom security mechanism?</span></span></h2>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","authorId":null,"subject":"linked-to-139","tags":["security"],"img":null,"summary":null,"lastUpdated":"2018-07-01T13:59:22.596+0000"}